    "PB",
    "stacked order block",
    "推进块"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "An order block formed when price retests and respects a prior order block, then a new opposing candle closes through it. The new candle becomes the propulsion block, with its opening price as a critical entry zone and its mean threshold (50% body) as an invalidation line. It signals reinforced institutional commitment and trend continuation.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a valid pre-existing order block where price has previously closed through opposing candles at an important level.",
    "Confirm price retraces and retests this order block; the retest should respect the order block's mean threshold rather than violating it.",
    "Wait for a new opposing candle (up-close for bullish, down-close for bearish) to trade into the order block and close through it, ideally after a sweep of a swing low/high.",
    "Mark this closing candle as the propulsion block; its opening price is the critical entry zone.",
    "Draw the mean threshold (50% of the propulsion block's body range); this level must hold on any subsequent retest — a close beyond it invalidates the setup.",
    "Validate by ensuring the propulsion block aligns with higher time frame bias and, optionally, confluence with other PD arrays such as fair value gaps.",
    "The propulsion block should be smaller in size than the original order block and located within or adjacent to it.",
    "Confirm the stacked structure is aligned with the prevailing higher time frame directional bias (e.g., a bearish propulsion block forms during a downtrend after a retest of a prior bearish OB).",
    "Look for additional confluences such as session time alignment (8:30, 9:30, midnight open) and overlapping reference levels to strengthen the setup.",
    "The propulsion block can be identified on lower time frames (e.g., 5-minute, 15-minute) as a precise entry for higher time frame continuation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Propulsion blocks offer a high-probability continuation entry after a successful order block retest. They allow for tighter stop placement at the propulsion block's extreme, mean threshold, or opening price, and are used to enter in the direction of the prevailing bias. Targets are typically the next liquidity pool (buy-side/sell-side), prior swing highs/lows, or a minimum 2R objective. The setup is most reliable when aligned with higher time frame direction. Price must hold above (for longs) or below (for shorts) the mean threshold to remain valid; a breach suggests invalidation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Labeling any retest of an order block as a propulsion block without confirming that a new, distinct series of same-direction candles has actually formed at the retest level.",
    "Entering before the opposing candle fully closes through the prior order block, or mistaking a wick for a valid closure.",
    "Holding the trade after price closes beyond the propulsion block's mean threshold.",
    "Using the concept on very low time frames (e.g., 5-minute) where signals become noisy and unreliable.",
    "Ignoring higher time frame bias, leading to counter-trend entries or failures in ranging markets.",
    "Assuming the mean threshold will hold without waiting for price to actually respect it on a retest.",
    "Placing stops based on the original order block instead of using the propulsion block's tighter invalidation levels (high/low or mean threshold).",
    "Misidentifying a propulsion block when the initial sweep did not cleanly close through the opposing candle series.",
    "Entering after multiple expansion candles have already formed, when the move is likely exhausted.",
    "Trusting an invalidation point that hasn't been swept to create high resistance liquidity (e.g., using an unswept low/high as invalidation).",
    "Entering on the original order block retest without waiting for the propulsion block's confirmation close, especially if the order block is not in a discount/premium zone.",
    "Confusing propulsion block with a regular order block; propulsion block must be derived from a prior order block's price leg.",
    "Using propulsion block as a reversal signal instead of a continuation structure.",
    "Entering before price actually retests and respects the stacked zone, rather than waiting for retest confirmation."
  ],
